  "text": "Like many intellectuals of his generation, Durkheim was influenced by organicist thinking: He turns to analogies with biological organisms to analyze human societies. In organicist thinking, individuals are analogous to the cells of an organism, and societies are analogous to the human body. For example, as the fetus grows and develops, clusters of embryonic cells (which were originally identical in structure and function) change and specialize, such that some become kidney cells, whereas others become blood cells or form the lungs. Durkheim (1893 [CITATION_1] suggests, for example, that the modern state becomes the \"social brain\" because it has \"directive power\" in a society (p. 84).",
